Clustering Methods - Wikipedia Articles & MNIST¶

In the following code, we explore different clustering methods applied on Wikipedia datasets and MNIST data.

The objectives are to observe if the clustering methods enable us to classify both the Wikipedia articles and MNIST dataset into their correct labels (For Wikipedia articles, these are the categories they belong under, and for MNIST, these are the digits).

"""
Clustering Functions
Note the following clustering functions will be used in subsequent parts.
"""

def kmeans_cluster(features, n_clusters, n_rounds=10, maxrun=300):
    """
    k-means clustering
    ------
    :in:
    features: 2d array of shape (n_data, n_dim), data to cluster
    n_clusters: int, number of clusters
    n_rounds: int, number of time the k-means algorithm will be run with different centroid seeds (default:5)
    maxrun: int, maximum iterations of the k-means for a single run (default: 300)
    :out:
    labels: 1d array of shape (n_data,), index of the cluster each data point belongs to
    """
    print("Using K-means!")
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, n_init=n_rounds, max_iter=maxrun)
    kmeans.fit(features)
    labels = kmeans.predict(features)
    return labels

def hierarchical_cluster(features, n_clusters, method, metric='euclidean'):
    """
    Agglomerative (Hierarchical) clustering
    ------
    :in:
    features: 2d array of shape (n_data, n_dim), data to cluster
    method: string, methods to compute distances between clusters
            Options: "single" | "complete" | "average" | "weighted" | "centroid" | "median" | "ward"
    metric: string, distance metric to use ((default: "euclidean"))
            See the "scipy.spatial.distance.pdist" for a list of valid distance metrics 
    :out:
    Z: 2d array of shape (4, n_data-1), linkage matrix
    labels, 1d array of shape (n_data,), index of the cluster each data point belongs to
    """
    print("Using hierarchical clustering!")
    vdist = pdist(features, metric=metric)
    Z = linkage(vdist, method=method, metric=metric)
    labels = utils.linkage_to_pred(Z, n_clusters)
    return Z, labels

def spectral_cluster(features, num_clusters, k_value=5, aff="nearest_neighbors", g=1):
    """
    :in:
    features: 2d array of shape (n_data, n_dim), data to cluster
    n_clusters: int, number of clusters
    :out:
    labels: 1d array of shape (n_data,), index of the cluster each data point belongs to
    """
    clustering_spec = SpectralClustering(n_clusters=num_clusters, n_init=10, affinity=aff, 
                                    n_neighbors=k_value, gamma=g, assign_labels='kmeans')
    results = clustering_spec.fit_predict(features)
    return results

Wikipedia Articles Document Clustering¶

Please refer to the comments in each cell on the process. For each Wikipedia articles we downloaded, we transformed the articles into a tf-idf matrix (bag-of-words model; more information is available here https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tf%E2%80%93idf), before using this information to cluster the documents.

"""
QUANTITATIVE COMPARISONS OF METHODS
Next, we will proceed with quantitative comparisons. First, we write functions for hyperparameter training
"""

#For Hierarchical clustering, we will test out with different methods, 
#and different definitions of distances
methods = ["ward", "single", "complete", "average", "weighted", "centroid"]
distance = ["cosine", "euclidean"]
def hierarchical_purity_nmi(methods, distance, n_level):
    purity_results = np.zeros((6,2))
    nmi_results = np.zeros((6,2))
    i = 0
    for m in methods:
        j = 0
        for d in distance:
            labels, titles, cats = utils.get_label(label_path, n_level)
            linkage_matrix, pred = hierarchical_cluster(fs.toarray(), n_clusters=len(cats), method=m, metric=d)
            _, cm, purity = get_purity(pred, labels)
            nmi = get_nmi(pred, labels)
            purity_results[i,j] = purity
            nmi_results[i,j] = nmi
            j = j+1
        i = i+1
    return purity_results, nmi_results

#K-Means quantitative comparison
def k_means_purity_nmi(n_level):
    labels, titles, cats = utils.get_label(label_path, n_level)
    pred = kmeans_cluster(fs, len(cats), n_rounds=15, maxrun=300)
    _, cm, purity = get_purity(pred, labels)
    nmi = get_nmi(pred, labels)
    return purity, nmi

#Spectral quantitative comparison
def spectral_purity_nmi(n_level, k_list):
    purity_results = np.repeat(0,len(k_list))
    nmi_results = np.repeat(0,len(k_list))
    for k_num in k_list:
        labels, titles, cats = utils.get_label(label_path, n_level)
        pred = spectral_cluster(fs, num_clusters=len(cats), k_value=k_num)
        _, cm, purity = get_purity(pred, labels)
        nmi = get_nmi(pred, labels)
        print(purity, nmi)

"""
3. Hierarchical clustering
Note: n_hier_samples is number of samples for hierarchical clustering. 
Setting it to 10000 is equivalent to using whole tuning set. 


First, let us select the best method and metric
"""

idx = sample_index(tune_y_sample, n_hier_samples)
